14 //
15 // Declaration of the core objects for the constraint solver.
16 //
17 // The literature around constraint programming is extremely dense but one
18 // can find some basic introductions in the following links:
19 // - http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constraint_programming
20 // - http://kti.mff.cuni.cz/~bartak/constraints/index.html
21 //
22 // Here is a very simple Constraint Programming problem:
23 //
24 // Knowing that we see 56 legs and 20 heads, how many pheasants and rabbits
25 // are we looking at?
26 //
27 // Here is some simple Constraint Programming code to find out:
28 //
29 // void pheasant() {
30 // Solver s("pheasant");
31 // IntVar* const p = s.MakeIntVar(0, 20, "pheasant"));
32 // IntVar* const r = s.MakeIntVar(0, 20, "rabbit"));
33 // IntExpr* const legs = s.MakeSum(s.MakeProd(p, 2), s.MakeProd(r, 4));
34 // IntExpr* const heads = s.MakeSum(p, r);
35 // Constraint* const ct_legs = s.MakeEquality(legs, 56);
36 // Constraint* const ct_heads = s.MakeEquality(heads, 20);
37 // s.AddConstraint(ct_legs);
38 // s.AddConstraint(ct_heads);
39 // DecisionBuilder* const db = s.MakePhase(p, r,
40 // Solver::CHOOSE_FIRST_UNBOUND,
41 // Solver::ASSIGN_MIN_VALUE);
42 // s.NewSearch(db);
43 // CHECK(s.NextSolution());
44 // LOG(INFO) << "rabbits -> " << r->Value() << ", pheasants -> "
45 // << p->Value();
46 // LOG(INFO) << s.DebugString();
47 // s.EndSearch();
48 // }
49 //
50 // which outputs:
51 //
52 // rabbits -> 8, pheasants -> 12
53 // Solver(name = "pheasant",
54 // state = OUTSIDE_SEARCH,
55 // branches = 0,
56 // fails = 0,
57 // decisions = 0
58 // propagation loops = 11,
59 // demons Run = 25,
60 // Run time = 0 ms)
61 //
62 //
63

153 // This struct holds all parameters for the default search.

169  enum DisplayLevel { NONE = 0, NORMAL = 1, VERBOSE = 2 };
170 
171  // This parameter describes how the next variable to instantiate
172  // will be chosen.
173  VariableSelection var_selection_schema;
174 
175  // This parameter describes which value to select for a given var.
176  ValueSelection value_selection_schema;
177 
178  // Maximum number of intervals that the initialization of impacts will scan
179  // per variable.
180  int initialization_splits;
181 
182  // The default phase will run heuristics periodically. This parameter
183  // indicates if we should run all heuristics, or a randomly selected
184  // one.
185  bool run_all_heuristics;
186 
187  // The distance in nodes between each run of the heuristics. A
188  // negative or null value will mean that we will not run heuristics
189  // at all.
190  int heuristic_period;
191 
192  // The failure limit for each heuristic that we run.
193  int heuristic_num_failures_limit;
194 
195  // Whether to keep the impact from the first search for other searches,
196  // or to recompute the impact for each new search.
197  bool persistent_impact;
198 
199  // Seed used to initialize the random part in some heuristics.
200  int random_seed;
201 
202  // This represents the amount of information displayed by the default search.
203  // NONE means no display, VERBOSE means extra information.
204  DisplayLevel display_level;
205 
206  // Should we use last conflict method. The default is false.
207  bool use_last_conflict;
208 
209  // When defined, this overrides the default impact based decision builder.
210  DecisionBuilder* decision_builder;
211 
212  DefaultPhaseParameters();

216 //
217 // Solver Class
218 //
219 // A solver represents the main computation engine. It implements the entire
220 // range of Constraint Programming protocols:
221 // - Reversibility
222 // - Propagation
223 // - Search
224 //
225 // Usually, Constraint Programming code consists of
226 // - the creation of the Solver,
227 // - the creation of the decision variables of the model,
228 // - the creation of the constraints of the model and their addition to the
229 // solver() through the AddConstraint() method,
230 // - the creation of the main DecisionBuilder class,
231 // - the launch of the solve() method with the decision builder.
232 //
233 // For the time being, Solver is neither MT_SAFE nor MT_HOT.
235 //
236 class Solver {
237  public:
238  // Holds semantic information stating that the 'expression' has been
239  // cast into 'variable' using the Var() method, and that
240  // 'maintainer' is responsible for maintaining the equality between
241  // 'variable' and 'expression'.
242  struct IntegerCastInfo {
243  IntegerCastInfo()
244  : variable(nullptr), expression(nullptr), maintainer(nullptr) {}
245  IntegerCastInfo(IntVar* const v, IntExpr* const e, Constraint* const c)
246  : variable(v), expression(e), maintainer(c) {}
247  IntVar* variable;
248  IntExpr* expression;
249  Constraint* maintainer;
250  };

255  // This enum describes the strategy used to select the next branching
256  // variable at each node during the search.
257  enum IntVarStrategy {
258  // The default behavior is CHOOSE_FIRST_UNBOUND.
259  INT_VAR_DEFAULT,
260 
261  // The simple selection is CHOOSE_FIRST_UNBOUND.
262  INT_VAR_SIMPLE,
263 
264  // Select the first unbound variable.
265  // Variables are considered in the order of the vector of IntVars used
266  // to create the selector.
267  CHOOSE_FIRST_UNBOUND,
268 
269  // Randomly select one of the remaining unbound variables.
270  CHOOSE_RANDOM,
271 
272  // Among unbound variables, select the variable with the smallest size,
273  // i.e., the smallest number of possible values.
274  // In case of a tie, the selected variables is the one with the lowest min
275  // value.
276  // In case of a tie, the first one is selected, first being defined by the
277  // order in the vector of IntVars used to create the selector.
278  CHOOSE_MIN_SIZE_LOWEST_MIN,
279 
280  // Among unbound variables, select the variable with the smallest size,
281  // i.e., the smallest number of possible values.
282  // In case of a tie, the selected variable is the one with the highest min
283  // value.
284  // In case of a tie, the first one is selected, first being defined by the
285  // order in the vector of IntVars used to create the selector.
286  CHOOSE_MIN_SIZE_HIGHEST_MIN,
287 
288  // Among unbound variables, select the variable with the smallest size,
289  // i.e., the smallest number of possible values.
290  // In case of a tie, the selected variables is the one with the lowest max
291  // value.
292  // In case of a tie, the first one is selected, first being defined by the
293  // order in the vector of IntVars used to create the selector.
294  CHOOSE_MIN_SIZE_LOWEST_MAX,
295 
296  // Among unbound variables, select the variable with the smallest size,
297  // i.e., the smallest number of possible values.
298  // In case of a tie, the selected variable is the one with the highest max
299  // value.
300  // In case of a tie, the first one is selected, first being defined by the
301  // order in the vector of IntVars used to create the selector.
302  CHOOSE_MIN_SIZE_HIGHEST_MAX,
303 
304  // Among unbound variables, select the variable with the smallest minimal
305  // value.
306  // In case of a tie, the first one is selected, "first" defined by the
307  // order in the vector of IntVars used to create the selector.
308  CHOOSE_LOWEST_MIN,
309 
310  // Among unbound variables, select the variable with the highest maximal
311  // value.
312  // In case of a tie, the first one is selected, first being defined by the
313  // order in the vector of IntVars used to create the selector.
314  CHOOSE_HIGHEST_MAX,
315 
316  // Among unbound variables, select the variable with the smallest size.
317  // In case of a tie, the first one is selected, first being defined by the
318  // order in the vector of IntVars used to create the selector.
319  CHOOSE_MIN_SIZE,
320 
321  // Among unbound variables, select the variable with the highest size.
322  // In case of a tie, the first one is selected, first being defined by the
323  // order in the vector of IntVars used to create the selector.
324  CHOOSE_MAX_SIZE,
325 
326  // Among unbound variables, select the variable with the largest
327  // gap between the first and the second values of the domain.
328  CHOOSE_MAX_REGRET_ON_MIN,
329 
330  // Selects the next unbound variable on a path, the path being defined by
331  // the variables: var[i] corresponds to the index of the next of i.
332  CHOOSE_PATH,
333  };
334  // TODO(user): add HIGHEST_MIN and LOWEST_MAX.

336  // This enum describes the strategy used to select the next variable value to
337  // set.
338  enum IntValueStrategy {
339  // The default behavior is ASSIGN_MIN_VALUE.
340  INT_VALUE_DEFAULT,
341 
342  // The simple selection is ASSIGN_MIN_VALUE.
343  INT_VALUE_SIMPLE,
344 
345  // Selects the min value of the selected variable.
346  ASSIGN_MIN_VALUE,
347 
348  // Selects the max value of the selected variable.
349  ASSIGN_MAX_VALUE,
350 
351  // Selects randomly one of the possible values of the selected variable.
352  ASSIGN_RANDOM_VALUE,
353 
354  // Selects the first possible value which is the closest to the center
355  // of the domain of the selected variable.
356  // The center is defined as (min + max) / 2.
357  ASSIGN_CENTER_VALUE,
358 
359  // Split the domain in two around the center, and choose the lower
360  // part first.
361  SPLIT_LOWER_HALF,
362 
363  // Split the domain in two around the center, and choose the lower
364  // part first.
365  SPLIT_UPPER_HALF,
366  };
367 
368  // This enum is used by Solver::MakePhase to specify how to select variables
369  // and values during the search.
370  // In Solver::MakePhase(const std::vector<IntVar*>&, IntVarStrategy,
371  // IntValueStrategy), variables are selected first, and then the associated
372  // value.
373  // In Solver::MakePhase(const std::vector<IntVar*>& vars, IndexEvaluator2,
374  // EvaluatorStrategy), the selection is done scanning every pair
375  // <variable, possible value>. The next selected pair is then the best among
376  // all possibilities, i.e. the pair with the smallest evaluation.
377  // As this is costly, two options are offered: static or dynamic evaluation.
378  enum EvaluatorStrategy {
379  // Pairs are compared at the first call of the selector, and results are
380  // cached. Next calls to the selector use the previous computation, and so
381  // are not up-to-date, e.g. some <variable, value> pairs may not be possible
382  // anymore due to propagation since the first to call.
383  CHOOSE_STATIC_GLOBAL_BEST,
384 
385  // Pairs are compared each time a variable is selected. That way all pairs
386  // are relevant and evaluation is accurate.
387  // This strategy runs in O(number-of-pairs) at each variable selection,
388  // versus O(1) in the static version.
389  CHOOSE_DYNAMIC_GLOBAL_BEST,
390  };
391

394  SEQUENCE_DEFAULT,
395  SEQUENCE_SIMPLE,
396  CHOOSE_MIN_SLACK_RANK_FORWARD,
397  CHOOSE_RANDOM_RANK_FORWARD,
398  };

400  // This enum describes the straregy used to select the next interval variable
401  // and its value to be fixed.
402  enum IntervalStrategy {
403  // The default is INTERVAL_SET_TIMES_FORWARD.
404  INTERVAL_DEFAULT,
405  // The simple is INTERVAL_SET_TIMES_FORWARD.
406  INTERVAL_SIMPLE,
407  // Selects the variable with the lowest starting time of all variables,
408  // and fixes its starting time to this lowest value.
409  INTERVAL_SET_TIMES_FORWARD,
410  // Selects the variable with the highest ending time of all variables,
411  // and fixes the ending time to this highest values.
412  INTERVAL_SET_TIMES_BACKWARD
413  };

415  // This enum is used in Solver::MakeOperator to specify the neighborhood to
416  // create.
417  enum LocalSearchOperators {
418  // Operator which reverses a sub-chain of a path. It is called TwoOpt
419  // because it breaks two arcs on the path; resulting paths are called
420  // two-optimal.
421  // Possible neighbors for the path 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 -> 5
422  // (where (1, 5) are first and last nodes of the path and can therefore not
423  // be moved):
424  // 1 -> [3 -> 2] -> 4 -> 5
425  // 1 -> [4 -> 3 -> 2] -> 5
426  // 1 -> 2 -> [4 -> 3] -> 5
427  TWOOPT,
428 
429  // Relocate: OROPT and RELOCATE.
430  // Operator which moves a sub-chain of a path to another position; the
431  // specified chain length is the fixed length of the chains being moved.
432  // When this length is 1, the operator simply moves a node to another
433  // position.
434  // Possible neighbors for the path 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 -> 5, for a chain
435  // length of 2 (where (1, 5) are first and last nodes of the path and can
436  // therefore not be moved):
437  // 1 -> 4 -> [2 -> 3] -> 5
438  // 1 -> [3 -> 4] -> 2 -> 5
439  //
440  // Using Relocate with chain lengths of 1, 2 and 3 together is equivalent
441  // to the OrOpt operator on a path. The OrOpt operator is a limited
442  // version of 3Opt (breaks 3 arcs on a path).
443  OROPT,
444 
445  // Relocate neighborhood with length of 1 (see OROPT comment).
446  RELOCATE,
447 
448  // Operator which exchanges the positions of two nodes.
449  // Possible neighbors for the path 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 -> 5
450  // (where (1, 5) are first and last nodes of the path and can therefore not
451  // be moved):
452  // 1 -> [3] -> [2] -> 4 -> 5
453  // 1 -> [4] -> 3 -> [2] -> 5
454  // 1 -> 2 -> [4] -> [3] -> 5
455  EXCHANGE,
456 
457  // Operator which cross exchanges the starting chains of 2 paths, including
458  // exchanging the whole paths.
459  // First and last nodes are not moved.
460  // Possible neighbors for the paths 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 -> 5 and 6 -> 7 -> 8
461  // (where (1, 5) and (6, 8) are first and last nodes of the paths and can
462  // therefore not be moved):
463  // 1 -> [7] -> 3 -> 4 -> 5 6 -> [2] -> 8
464  // 1 -> [7] -> 4 -> 5 6 -> [2 -> 3] -> 8
465  // 1 -> [7] -> 5 6 -> [2 -> 3 -> 4] -> 8
466  CROSS,
467 
468  // Operator which inserts an inactive node into a path.
469  // Possible neighbors for the path 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 with 5 inactive
470  // (where 1 and 4 are first and last nodes of the path) are:
471  // 1 -> [5] -> 2 -> 3 -> 4
472  // 1 -> 2 -> [5] -> 3 -> 4
473  // 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> [5] -> 4
474  MAKEACTIVE,
475 
476  // Operator which makes path nodes inactive.
477  // Possible neighbors for the path 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 (where 1 and 4 are
478  // first and last nodes of the path) are:
479  // 1 -> 3 -> 4 with 2 inactive
480  // 1 -> 2 -> 4 with 3 inactive
481  MAKEINACTIVE,
482 
483  // Operator which makes a "chain" of path nodes inactive.
484  // Possible neighbors for the path 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 (where 1 and 4 are
485  // first and last nodes of the path) are:
486  // 1 -> 3 -> 4 with 2 inactive
487  // 1 -> 2 -> 4 with 3 inactive
488  // 1 -> 4 with 2 and 3 inactive
489  MAKECHAININACTIVE,
490 
491  // Operator which replaces an active node by an inactive one.
492  // Possible neighbors for the path 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 with 5 inactive
493  // (where 1 and 4 are first and last nodes of the path) are:
494  // 1 -> [5] -> 3 -> 4 with 2 inactive
495  // 1 -> 2 -> [5] -> 4 with 3 inactive
496  SWAPACTIVE,
497 
498  // Operator which makes an inactive node active and an active one inactive.
499  // It is similar to SwapActiveOperator except that it tries to insert the
500  // inactive node in all possible positions instead of just the position of
501  // the node made inactive.
502  // Possible neighbors for the path 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 with 5 inactive
503  // (where 1 and 4 are first and last nodes of the path) are:
504  // 1 -> [5] -> 3 -> 4 with 2 inactive
505  // 1 -> 3 -> [5] -> 4 with 2 inactive
506  // 1 -> [5] -> 2 -> 4 with 3 inactive
507  // 1 -> 2 -> [5] -> 4 with 3 inactive
508  EXTENDEDSWAPACTIVE,
509 
510  // Operator which relaxes two sub-chains of three consecutive arcs each.
511  // Each sub-chain is defined by a start node and the next three arcs. Those
512  // six arcs are relaxed to build a new neighbor.
513  // PATHLNS explores all possible pairs of starting nodes and so defines
514  // n^2 neighbors, n being the number of nodes.
515  // Note that the two sub-chains can be part of the same path; they even may
516  // overlap.
517  PATHLNS,
518 
519  // Operator which relaxes one entire path and all inactive nodes, thus
520  // defining num_paths neighbors.
521  FULLPATHLNS,
522 
523  // Operator which relaxes all inactive nodes and one sub-chain of six
524  // consecutive arcs. That way the path can be improved by inserting
525  // inactive nodes or swapping arcs.
526  UNACTIVELNS,
527 
528  // Operator which defines one neighbor per variable. Each neighbor tries to
529  // increment by one the value of the corresponding variable. When a new
530  // solution is found the neighborhood is rebuilt from scratch, i.e., tries
531  // to increment values in the variable order.
532  // Consider for instance variables x and y. x is incremented one by one to
533  // its max, and when it is not possible to increment x anymore, y is
534  // incremented once. If this is a solution, then next neighbor tries to
535  // increment x.
536  INCREMENT,
537 
538  // Operator which defines a neighborhood to decrement values.
539  // The behavior is the same as INCREMENT, except values are decremented
540  // instead of incremented.
541  DECREMENT,
542 
543  // Operator which defines one neighbor per variable. Each neighbor relaxes
544  // one variable.
545  // When a new solution is found the neighborhood is rebuilt from scratch.
546  // Consider for instance variables x and y. First x is relaxed and the
547  // solver is looking for the best possible solution (with only x relaxed).
548  // Then y is relaxed, and the solver is looking for a new solution.
549  // If a new solution is found, then the next variable to be relaxed is x.
550  SIMPLELNS
551  };
552 
553  // This enum is used in Solver::MakeOperator associated with an evaluator
554  // to specify the neighborhood to create.
555  enum EvaluatorLocalSearchOperators {
556  // LinKernighan local search.
557  // While the accumulated local gain is positive, perform a 2opt or a 3opt
558  // move followed by a series of 2opt moves. Return a neighbor for which the
559  // global gain is positive.
560  LK,
561 
562  // Sliding TSP operator.
563  // Uses an exact dynamic programming algorithm to solve the TSP
564  // corresponding to path sub-chains.
565  // For a subchain 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 -> 5 -> 6, solves the TSP on
566  // nodes A, 2, 3, 4, 5, where A is a merger of nodes 1 and 6 such that
567  // cost(A,i) = cost(1,i) and cost(i,A) = cost(i,6).
568  TSPOPT,
569 
570  // TSP-base LNS.
571  // Randomly merge consecutive nodes until n "meta"-nodes remain and solve
572  // the corresponding TSP.
573  // This is an "unlimited" neighborhood which must be stopped by search
574  // limits. To force diversification, the operator iteratively forces each
575  // node to serve as base of a meta-node.
576  TSPLNS
577  };
578 
579  // This enum is used in Solver::MakeLocalSearchObjectiveFilter. It specifies
580  // the behavior of the objective filter to create. The goal is to define
581  // under which condition a move is accepted based on the current objective
582  // value.
583  enum LocalSearchFilterBound {
584  // Move is accepted when the current objective value >= objective.Min.
585  GE,
586  // Move is accepted when the current objective value <= objective.Max.
587  LE,
588  // Move is accepted when the current objective value is in the interval
589  // objective.Min .. objective.Max.
590  EQ
591  };

593  // This enum represents the three possible priorities for a demon in the
594  // Solver queue.
595  // Note: this is for advanced users only.
596  enum DemonPriority {
597  // DELAYED_PRIORITY is the lowest priority: Demons will be processed after
598  // VAR_PRIORITY and NORMAL_PRIORITY demons.
599  DELAYED_PRIORITY = 0,
600 
601  // VAR_PRIORITY is between DELAYED_PRIORITY and NORMAL_PRIORITY.
602  VAR_PRIORITY = 1,
603 
604  // NORMAL_PRIORITY is the highest priority: Demons will be processed first.
605  NORMAL_PRIORITY = 2,
606  };

608  // This enum is used in Solver::MakeIntervalVarRelation to specify the
609  // temporal relation between the two intervals t1 and t2.
610  enum BinaryIntervalRelation {
611  // t1 ends after t2 end, i.e. End(t1) >= End(t2) + delay.
612  ENDS_AFTER_END,
613 
614  // t1 ends after t2 start, i.e. End(t1) >= Start(t2) + delay.
615  ENDS_AFTER_START,
616 
617  // t1 ends at t2 end, i.e. End(t1) == End(t2) + delay.
618  ENDS_AT_END,
619 
620  // t1 ends at t2 start, i.e. End(t1) == Start(t2) + delay.
621  ENDS_AT_START,
622 
623  // t1 starts after t2 end, i.e. Start(t1) >= End(t2) + delay.
624  STARTS_AFTER_END,
625 
626  // t1 starts after t2 start, i.e. Start(t1) >= Start(t2) + delay.
627  STARTS_AFTER_START,
628 
629  // t1 starts at t2 end, i.e. Start(t1) == End(t2) + delay.
630  STARTS_AT_END,
631 
632  // t1 starts at t2 start, i.e. Start(t1) == Start(t2) + delay.
633  STARTS_AT_START,
634 
635  // STARTS_AT_START and ENDS_AT_END at the same time.
636  // t1 starts at t2 start, i.e. Start(t1) == Start(t2) + delay.
637  // t1 ends at t2 end, i.e. End(t1) == End(t2).
638  STAYS_IN_SYNC
639  };
640 
641  // This enum is used in Solver::MakeIntervalVarRelation to specify the
642  // temporal relation between an interval t and an integer d.
643  enum UnaryIntervalRelation {
644  // t ends after d, i.e. End(t) >= d.
645  ENDS_AFTER,
646 
647  // t ends at d, i.e. End(t) == d.
648  ENDS_AT,
649 
650  // t ends before d, i.e. End(t) <= d.
651  ENDS_BEFORE,
652 
653  // t starts after d, i.e. Start(t) >= d.
654  STARTS_AFTER,
655 
656  // t starts at d, i.e. Start(t) == d.
657  STARTS_AT,
658 
659  // t starts before d, i.e. Start(t) <= d.
660  STARTS_BEFORE,
661 
662  // STARTS_BEFORE and ENDS_AFTER at the same time, i.e. d is in t.
663  // t starts before d, i.e. Start(t) <= d.
664  // t ends after d, i.e. End(t) >= d.
665  CROSS_DATE,
666 
667  // STARTS_AFTER or ENDS_BEFORE, i.e. d is not in t.
668  // t starts after d, i.e. Start(t) >= d.
669  // t ends before d, i.e. End(t) <= d.
670  AVOID_DATE
671  };
672 
673  // The Solver is responsible for creating the search tree. Thanks to the
674  // DecisionBuilder, it creates a new decision with two branches at each node:
675  // left and right.
676  // The DecisionModification enum is used to specify how the branch selector
677  // should behave.
678  enum DecisionModification {
679  // Keeps the default behavior, i.e. apply left branch first, and then right
680  // branch in case of backtracking.
681  NO_CHANGE,
682 
683  // Right branches are ignored. This is used to make the code faster when
684  // backtrack makes no sense or is not useful.
685  // This is faster as there is no need to create one new node per decision.
686  KEEP_LEFT,
687 
688  // Left branches are ignored. This is used to make the code faster when
689  // backtrack makes no sense or is not useful.
690  // This is faster as there is no need to create one new node per decision.
691  KEEP_RIGHT,
692 
693  // Backtracks to the previous decisions, i.e. left and right branches are
694  // not applied.
695  KILL_BOTH,
696 
697  // Applies right branch first. Left branch will be applied in case of
698  // backtracking.
699  SWITCH_BRANCHES
700  };
701 
702  // This enum is used internally in private methods Solver::PushState and
703  // Solver::PopState to tag states in the search tree.
704  enum MarkerType { SENTINEL, SIMPLE_MARKER, CHOICE_POINT, REVERSIBLE_ACTION };
705 
706  // This enum represents the state of the solver w.r.t. the search.
707  enum SolverState {
708  OUTSIDE_SEARCH, // Before search, after search.
709  IN_ROOT_NODE, // Executing the root node.
710  IN_SEARCH, // Executing the search code.
711  AT_SOLUTION, // After successful NextSolution and before EndSearch.
712  NO_MORE_SOLUTIONS, // After failed NextSolution and before EndSearch.
713  PROBLEM_INFEASIBLE // After search, the model is infeasible.
714  };

717  enum OptimizationDirection { NOT_SET, MAXIMIZATION, MINIMIZATION };

751  // reversibility
752 
753  // SaveValue() saves the value of the corresponding object. It must be
754  // called before modifying the object. The value will be restored upon
755  // backtrack.
756  template <class T>
757  void SaveValue(T* o) {
758  InternalSaveValue(o);
759  }
760 
761  // Registers the given object as being reversible. By calling this method,
762  // the caller gives ownership of the object to the solver, which will
763  // delete it when there is a backtrack out of the current state.
764  //
765  // Returns the argument for convenience: this way, the caller may directly
766  // invoke a constructor in the argument, without having to store the pointer
767  // first.
768  //
769  // This function is only for users that define their own subclasses of
770  // BaseObject: for all subclasses predefined in the library, the
771  // corresponding factory methods (e.g., MakeIntVar(...),
772  // MakeAllDifferent(...) already take care of the registration.
773  template <typename T>
774  T* RevAlloc(T* object) {
775  return reinterpret_cast<T*>(SafeRevAlloc(object));
776  }
777 
778  // Like RevAlloc() above, but for an array of objects: the array
779  // must have been allocated with the new[] operator. The entire array
780  // will be deleted when backtracking out of the current state.
781  //
782  // This method is valid for arrays of int, int64, uint64, bool,
783  // BaseObject*, IntVar*, IntExpr*, and Constraint*.
784  template <typename T>
785  T* RevAllocArray(T* object) {
786  return reinterpret_cast<T*>(SafeRevAllocArray(object));
787  }
788 
789  // propagation
790 
791  // Adds the constraint 'c' to the model.
792  //
793  // After calling this method, and until there is a backtrack that undoes the
794  // addition, any assignment of variables to values must satisfy the given
795  // constraint in order to be considered feasible. There are two fairly
796  // different use cases:
797  //
798  // - the most common use case is modeling: the given constraint is really
799  // part of the problem that the user is trying to solve. In this use case,
800  // AddConstraint is called outside of search (i.e., with <tt>state() ==
801  // OUTSIDE_SEARCH</tt>). Most users should only use AddConstraint in this
802  // way. In this case, the constraint will belong to the model forever: it
803  // cannot not be removed by backtracking.
804  //
805  // - a rarer use case is that 'c' is not a real constraint of the model. It
806  // may be a constraint generated by a branching decision (a constraint whose
807  // goal is to restrict the search space), a symmetry breaking constraint (a
808  // constraint that does restrict the search space, but in a way that cannot
809  // have an impact on the quality of the solutions in the subtree), or an
810  // inferred constraint that, while having no semantic value to the model (it
811  // does not restrict the set of solutions), is worth having because we
812  // believe it may strengthen the propagation. In these cases, it happens
813  // that the constraint is added during the search (i.e., with state() ==
814  // IN_SEARCH or state() == IN_ROOT_NODE). When a constraint is
815  // added during a search, it applies only to the subtree of the search tree
816  // rooted at the current node, and will be automatically removed by
817  // backtracking.
818  //
819  // This method does not take ownership of the constraint. If the constraint
820  // has been created by any factory method (Solver::MakeXXX), it will
821  // automatically be deleted. However, power users who implement their own
822  // constraints should do: solver.AddConstraint(solver.RevAlloc(new
823  // MyConstraint(...));
824  void AddConstraint(Constraint* const c);
825  // Adds 'constraint' to the solver and marks it as a cast constraint, that
826  // is, a constraint created calling Var() on an expression. This is used
827  // internally.
828  void AddCastConstraint(CastConstraint* const constraint,
829  IntVar* const target_var, IntExpr* const expr);
830 
831  // @{
832  // Solves the problem using the given DecisionBuilder and returns true if a
833  // solution was found and accepted.
834  //
835  // These methods are the ones most users should use to search for a solution.
836  // Note that the definition of 'solution' is subtle. A solution here is
837  // defined as a leaf of the search tree with respect to the given decision
838  // builder for which there is no failure. What this means is that, contrary
839  // to intuition, a solution may not have all variables of the model bound.
840  // It is the responsibility of the decision builder to keep returning
841  // decisions until all variables are indeed bound. The most extreme
842  // counterexample is calling Solve with a trivial decision builder whose
843  // Next() method always returns nullptr. In this case, Solve immediately
844  // returns 'true', since not assigning any variable to any value is a
845  // solution, unless the root node propagation discovers that the model is
846  // infeasible.
847  //
848  // This function must be called either from outside of search,
849  // or from within the Next() method of a decision builder.
850  //
851  // Solve will terminate whenever any of the following event arise:
852  // * A search monitor asks the solver to terminate the search by calling
853  // solver()->FinishCurrentSearch().
854  // * A solution is found that is accepted by all search monitors, and none of
855  // the search monitors decides to search for another one.
856  //
857  // Upon search termination, there will be a series of backtracks all the way
858  // to the top level. This means that a user cannot expect to inspect the
859  // solution by querying variables after a call to Solve(): all the
860  // information will be lost. In order to do something with the solution, the
861  // user must either:
862  //
863  // * Use a search monitor that can process such a leaf. See, in particular,
864  // the SolutionCollector class.
865  // * Do not use Solve. Instead, use the more fine-grained approach using
866  // methods NewSearch(...), NextSolution(), and EndSearch().
867  //
868  // @param db The decision builder that will generate the search tree.
869  // @param monitors A vector of search monitors that will be notified of
870  // various events during the search. In their reaction to these events, such
871  // monitors may influence the search.
872  bool Solve(DecisionBuilder* const db,
873  const std::vector<SearchMonitor*>& monitors);
874  bool Solve(DecisionBuilder* const db);
875  bool Solve(DecisionBuilder* const db, SearchMonitor* const m1);
876  bool Solve(DecisionBuilder* const db, SearchMonitor* const m1,
877  SearchMonitor* const m2);
878  bool Solve(DecisionBuilder* const db, SearchMonitor* const m1,
879  SearchMonitor* const m2, SearchMonitor* const m3);
880  bool Solve(DecisionBuilder* const db, SearchMonitor* const m1,
881  SearchMonitor* const m2, SearchMonitor* const m3,
882  SearchMonitor* const m4);
883  // @}
884 
885  // @{
886  // Decomposed search.
887  // The code for a top level search should look like
888  // solver->NewSearch(db);
889  // while (solver->NextSolution()) {
890  // //.. use the current solution
891  // }
892  // solver()->EndSearch();
893 
894  void NewSearch(DecisionBuilder* const db,
895  const std::vector<SearchMonitor*>& monitors);
896  void NewSearch(DecisionBuilder* const db);
897  void NewSearch(DecisionBuilder* const db, SearchMonitor* const m1);
898  void NewSearch(DecisionBuilder* const db, SearchMonitor* const m1,
899  SearchMonitor* const m2);
900  void NewSearch(DecisionBuilder* const db, SearchMonitor* const m1,
901  SearchMonitor* const m2, SearchMonitor* const m3);
902  void NewSearch(DecisionBuilder* const db, SearchMonitor* const m1,
903  SearchMonitor* const m2, SearchMonitor* const m3,
904  SearchMonitor* const m4);
905 
906  bool NextSolution();

908  void EndSearch();
909  // @}

911  // SolveAndCommit using a decision builder and up to three
912  // search monitors, usually one for the objective, one for the limits
913  // and one to collect solutions.
914  //
915  // The difference between a SolveAndCommit() and a Solve() method
916  // call is the fact that SolveAndCommit will not backtrack all
917  // modifications at the end of the search. This method is only
918  // usable during the Next() method of a decision builder.
919  bool SolveAndCommit(DecisionBuilder* const db,

922  bool SolveAndCommit(DecisionBuilder* const db, SearchMonitor* const m1);
923  bool SolveAndCommit(DecisionBuilder* const db, SearchMonitor* const m1,
924  SearchMonitor* const m2);

1500  // Creates a constraint binding the arrays of variables "vars" and
1501  // "sorted_vars": sorted_vars[0] must be equal to the minimum of all
1502  // variables in vars, and so on: the value of sorted_vars[i] must be
1503  // equal to the i-th value of variables invars.
1504  //
1505  // This constraint propagates in both directions: from "vars" to
1506  // "sorted_vars" and vice-versa.
1507  //
1508  // Behind the scenes, this constraint maintains that:
1509  // - sorted is always increasing.
1510  // - whatever the values of vars, there exists a permutation that
1511  // injects its values into the sorted variables.
1512  //
1513  // For more info, please have a look at:
1514  // https://mpi-inf.mpg.de/~mehlhorn/ftp/Mehlhorn-Thiel.pdf
1515  Constraint* MakeSortingConstraint(const std::vector<IntVar*>& vars,
1516  const std::vector<IntVar*>& sorted);
1517  // TODO(user): Add void MakeSortedArray(const std::vector<IntVar*>& vars,
1518  // std::vector<IntVar*>* const
1519  // sorted);

1535  Constraint* MakeInversePermutationConstraint(

1567  // Prevent cycles. The "nexts" variables represent the next in the chain.
1568  // "active" variables indicate if the corresponding next variable is active;
1569  // this could be useful to model unperformed nodes in a routing problem.
1570  // A callback can be added to specify sink values (by default sink values
1571  // are values >= vars.size()). Ownership of the callback is passed to the
1572  // constraint.
1573  // If assume_paths is either not specified or true, the constraint assumes
1574  // the "nexts" variables represent paths (and performs a faster propagation);
1575  // otherwise the constraint assumes they represent a forest.
1576  Constraint* MakeNoCycle(const std::vector<IntVar*>& nexts,
1577  const std::vector<IntVar*>& active,
1578  IndexFilter1 sink_handler = nullptr);
1579  Constraint* MakeNoCycle(const std::vector<IntVar*>& nexts,
1580  const std::vector<IntVar*>& active,
1581  IndexFilter1 sink_handler, bool assume_paths);

1584  Constraint* MakeCircuit(const std::vector<IntVar*>& nexts);
1585 
1586  // Force the "nexts" variable to create a complete Hamiltonian path
1587  // for those that do not loop upon themselves.
1588  Constraint* MakeSubCircuit(const std::vector<IntVar*>& nexts);
1589 
1590  // Creates a constraint which accumulates values along a path such that:
1591  // cumuls[next[i]] = cumuls[i] + transits[i].
1592  // Active variables indicate if the corresponding next variable is active;
1593  // this could be useful to model unperformed nodes in a routing problem.
1594  Constraint* MakePathCumul(const std::vector<IntVar*>& nexts,
1595  const std::vector<IntVar*>& active,
1596  const std::vector<IntVar*>& cumuls,
1597  const std::vector<IntVar*>& transits);

1599  // is delayed until all constraints have propagated.
1600  // TODO(user): Merge with other path-cumuls constraints.
1601  Constraint* MakeDelayedPathCumul(const std::vector<IntVar*>& nexts,

1603  const std::vector<IntVar*>& cumuls,
1604  const std::vector<IntVar*>& transits);
1605  // Creates a constraint which accumulates values along a path such that:
1606  // cumuls[next[i]] = cumuls[i] + transit_evaluator(i, next[i]).
1607  // Active variables indicate if the corresponding next variable is active;
1608  // this could be useful to model unperformed nodes in a routing problem.
1609  // Ownership of transit_evaluator is taken and it must be a repeatable
1610  // callback.
1611  Constraint* MakePathCumul(const std::vector<IntVar*>& nexts,
1612  const std::vector<IntVar*>& active,
1613  const std::vector<IntVar*>& cumuls,
1614  IndexEvaluator2 transit_evaluator);
1615

1619  // this could be useful to model unperformed nodes in a routing problem.
1620  // Ownership of transit_evaluator is taken and it must be a repeatable
1621  // callback.
1622  Constraint* MakePathCumul(const std::vector<IntVar*>& nexts,

1635 #ifndef SWIG
1636  // Contraint enforcing, for each pair (i,j) in precedences, i to be before j
1637  // in paths defined by next variables.
1638  // TODO(user): This constraint does not make holes in variable domains;
1639  // the implementation can easily be modified to do that; evaluate the impact
1640  // on models solved with local search.
1641  Constraint* MakePathPrecedenceConstraint(
1642  std::vector<IntVar*> nexts,
1643  const std::vector<std::pair<int, int>>& precedences);
1644  // Same as MakePathPrecedenceConstraint but ensures precedence pairs on some
1645  // paths follow a LIFO or FIFO order.
1646  // LIFO order: given 2 pairs (a,b) and (c,d), if a is before c on the path
1647  // then d must be before b or b must be before c.
1648  // FIFO order: given 2 pairs (a,b) and (c,d), if a is before c on the path
1649  // then b must be before d.
1650  // LIFO (resp. FIFO) orders are enforced only on paths starting by indices in
1651  // lifo_path_starts (resp. fifo_path_start).
1652  Constraint* MakePathPrecedenceConstraint(
1653  std::vector<IntVar*> nexts,
1654  const std::vector<std::pair<int, int>>& precedences,
1655  const std::vector<int>& lifo_path_starts,
1656  const std::vector<int>& fifo_path_starts);
1657  // Same as MakePathPrecedenceConstraint but will force i to be before j if
1658  // the sum of transits on the path from i to j is strictly positive.
1659  Constraint* MakePathTransitPrecedenceConstraint(
1660  std::vector<IntVar*> nexts, std::vector<IntVar*> transits,
1661  const std::vector<std::pair<int, int>>& precedences);
1662 #endif

1666  Constraint* MakeMapDomain(IntVar* const var,
1667  const std::vector<IntVar*>& actives);

1669  // This method creates a constraint where the graph of the relation
1670  // between the variables is given in extension. There are 'arity'
1671  // variables involved in the relation and the graph is given by a
1672  // integer tuple set.
1673  Constraint* MakeAllowedAssignments(const std::vector<IntVar*>& vars,
1674  const IntTupleSet& tuples);
1675 
1676  // This constraint create a finite automaton that will check the
1677  // sequence of variables vars. It uses a transition table called
1678  // 'transition_table'. Each transition is a triple
1679  // (current_state, variable_value, new_state).
1680  // The initial state is given, and the set of accepted states is decribed
1681  // by 'final_states'. These states are hidden inside the constraint.
1682  // Only the transitions (i.e. the variables) are visible.
1683  Constraint* MakeTransitionConstraint(const std::vector<IntVar*>& vars,
1684  const IntTupleSet& transition_table,
1685  int64 initial_state,
1686  const std::vector<int64>& final_states);
1687 
1688  // This constraint create a finite automaton that will check the
1689  // sequence of variables vars. It uses a transition table called
1690  // 'transition_table'. Each transition is a triple
1691  // (current_state, variable_value, new_state).
1692  // The initial state is given, and the set of accepted states is decribed
1693  // by 'final_states'. These states are hidden inside the constraint.
1694  // Only the transitions (i.e. the variables) are visible.
1695  Constraint* MakeTransitionConstraint(const std::vector<IntVar*>& vars,
1696  const IntTupleSet& transition_table,
1697  int64 initial_state,
1698  const std::vector<int>& final_states);
1699 
1700 #if defined(SWIGPYTHON)
1701  // Compatibility layer for Python API.
1702  Constraint* MakeAllowedAssignments(
1703  const std::vector<IntVar*>& vars,
1704  const std::vector<std::vector<int64>>& raw_tuples) {
1705  IntTupleSet tuples(vars.size());
1706  tuples.InsertAll(raw_tuples);
1707  return MakeAllowedAssignments(vars, tuples);
1708  }
1709 
1710  Constraint* MakeTransitionConstraint(
1711  const std::vector<IntVar*>& vars,
1712  const std::vector<std::vector<int64>>& raw_transitions,
1713  int64 initial_state, const std::vector<int>& final_states) {
1714  IntTupleSet transitions(3);
1715  transitions.InsertAll(raw_transitions);
1716  return MakeTransitionConstraint(vars, transitions, initial_state,
1717  final_states);
1718  }
1719 #endif

1721  // This constraint states that all the boxes must not overlap.
1722  // The coordinates of box i are:
1723  // (x_vars[i], y_vars[i]),
1724  // (x_vars[i], y_vars[i] + y_size[i]),
1725  // (x_vars[i] + x_size[i], y_vars[i]),
1726  // (x_vars[i] + x_size[i], y_vars[i] + y_size[i]).
1727  // The sizes must be non-negative. Boxes with a zero dimension can be
1728  // pushed like any box.
1729  Constraint* MakeNonOverlappingBoxesConstraint(
1730  const std::vector<IntVar*>& x_vars, const std::vector<IntVar*>& y_vars,
1731  const std::vector<IntVar*>& x_size, const std::vector<IntVar*>& y_size);
1732  Constraint* MakeNonOverlappingBoxesConstraint(
1733  const std::vector<IntVar*>& x_vars, const std::vector<IntVar*>& y_vars,
1734  const std::vector<int64>& x_size, const std::vector<int64>& y_size);
1735  Constraint* MakeNonOverlappingBoxesConstraint(
1736  const std::vector<IntVar*>& x_vars, const std::vector<IntVar*>& y_vars,
1737  const std::vector<int>& x_size, const std::vector<int>& y_size);
1738 
1739  // This constraint states that all the boxes must not overlap.
1740  // The coordinates of box i are:
1741  // (x_vars[i], y_vars[i]),
1742  // (x_vars[i], y_vars[i] + y_size[i]),
1743  // (x_vars[i] + x_size[i], y_vars[i]),
1744  // (x_vars[i] + x_size[i], y_vars[i] + y_size[i]).
1745  // The sizes must be positive.
1746  // Boxes with a zero dimension can be placed anywhere.
1747  Constraint* MakeNonOverlappingNonStrictBoxesConstraint(

1882  // Creates and returns an interval variable that wraps around the given one,
1883  // relaxing the min start and end. Relaxing means making unbounded when
1884  // optional. If the variable is non-optional, this method returns
1885  // interval_var.
1886  //
1887  // More precisely, such an interval variable behaves as follows:
1888  // * When the underlying must be performed, the returned interval variable
1889  // behaves exactly as the underlying;
1890  // * When the underlying may or may not be performed, the returned interval
1891  // variable behaves like the underlying, except that it is unbounded on
1892  // the min side;
1893  // * When the underlying cannot be performed, the returned interval variable
1894  // is of duration 0 and must be performed in an interval unbounded on both
1895  // sides.
1896  //
1897  // This is very useful to implement propagators that may only modify
1898  // the start max or end max.
1899  IntervalVar* MakeIntervalRelaxedMin(IntervalVar* const interval_var);
1900 
1901  // Creates and returns an interval variable that wraps around the given one,
1902  // relaxing the max start and end. Relaxing means making unbounded when
1903  // optional. If the variable is non optional, this method returns
1904  // interval_var.
1905  //
1906  // More precisely, such an interval variable behaves as follows:
1907  // * When the underlying must be performed, the returned interval variable
1908  // behaves exactly as the underlying;
1909  // * When the underlying may or may not be performed, the returned interval
1910  // variable behaves like the underlying, except that it is unbounded on
1911  // the max side;
1912  // * When the underlying cannot be performed, the returned interval variable
1913  // is of duration 0 and must be performed in an interval unbounded on
1914  // both sides.
1915  //
1916  // This is very useful for implementing propagators that may only modify
1917  // the start min or end min.
1918  IntervalVar* MakeIntervalRelaxedMax(IntervalVar* const interval_var);

2145  // ----- Meta-heuristics -----
2146  // Search monitors which try to get the search out of local optima.
2147 
2148  // Creates a Tabu Search monitor.
2149  // In the context of local search the behavior is similar to MakeOptimize(),
2150  // creating an objective in a given sense. The behavior differs once a local
2151  // optimum is reached: thereafter solutions which degrade the value of the
2152  // objective are allowed if they are not "tabu". A solution is "tabu" if it
2153  // doesn't respect the following rules:
2154  // - improving the best solution found so far
2155  // - variables in the "keep" list must keep their value, variables in the
2156  // "forbid" list must not take the value they have in the list.
2157  // Variables with new values enter the tabu lists after each new solution
2158  // found and leave the lists after a given number of iterations (called
2159  // tenure). Only the variables passed to the method can enter the lists.
2160  // The tabu criterion is softened by the tabu factor which gives the number
2161  // of "tabu" violations which is tolerated; a factor of 1 means no violations
2162  // allowed; a factor of 0 means all violations are allowed.
2163 
2164  SearchMonitor* MakeTabuSearch(bool maximize, IntVar* const v, int64 step,
2165  const std::vector<IntVar*>& vars,
2166  int64 keep_tenure, int64 forbid_tenure,
2167  double tabu_factor);
2168 
2169  // Creates a Tabu Search based on the vars |vars|.
2170  // A solution is "tabu" if all the vars in |vars| keep their value.
2171  SearchMonitor* MakeGenericTabuSearch(bool maximize, IntVar* const v,
2172  int64 step,
2173  const std::vector<IntVar*>& tabu_vars,
2174  int64 forbid_tenure);
2175 
2176  // Creates a Simulated Annealing monitor.
2177  // TODO(user): document behavior
2178  SearchMonitor* MakeSimulatedAnnealing(bool maximize, IntVar* const v,
2179  int64 step, int64 initial_temperature);
2180 
2181  // Creates a Guided Local Search monitor.
2182  // Description here: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guided_Local_Search
2183  SearchMonitor* MakeGuidedLocalSearch(bool maximize, IntVar* const objective,
2184  IndexEvaluator2 objective_function,
2185  int64 step,
2186  const std::vector<IntVar*>& vars,
2187  double penalty_factor);
2188  SearchMonitor* MakeGuidedLocalSearch(
2189  bool maximize, IntVar* const objective,
2190  IndexEvaluator3 objective_function, int64 step,
2191  const std::vector<IntVar*>& vars,
2192  const std::vector<IntVar*>& secondary_vars, double penalty_factor);

2196  // This search monitor will restart the search periodically.
2197  // At the iteration n, it will restart after scale_factor * Luby(n) failures
2198  // where Luby is the Luby Strategy (i.e. 1 1 2 1 1 2 4 1 1 2 1 1 2 4 8...).
2199  SearchMonitor* MakeLubyRestart(int scale_factor);

2202  // failures.

2351  // Creates a decision builder which sequentially composes decision builders.

2353  // called. For instance, Compose(db1, db2) will result in the following tree:
2354  // d1 tree |
2355  // / | \ |
2356  // db1 leaves |
2357  // / | \ |
2358  // db2 tree db2 tree db2 tree |

2370  // Creates a decision builder which will create a search tree where each
2371  // decision builder is called from the top of the search tree. For instance
2372  // the decision builder Try(db1, db2) will entirely explore the search tree
2373  // of db1 then the one of db2, resulting in the following search tree:
2374  // Tree root |
2375  // / \ |
2376  // db1 tree db2 tree |
2377  //
2378  // This is very handy to try a decision builder which partially explores the
2379  // search space and if it fails to try another decision builder.
2380  //
2381  // TODO(user): The search tree can be balanced by using binary
2382  // "Try"-builders "recursively". For instance, Try(a,b,c,d) will give a tree
2383  // unbalanced to the right, whereas Try(Try(a,b), Try(b,c)) will give a
2384  // balanced tree. Investigate if we should only provide the binary version
2385  // and/or if we should balance automatically.
2386  DecisionBuilder* Try(DecisionBuilder* const db1, DecisionBuilder* const db2);
2387  DecisionBuilder* Try(DecisionBuilder* const db1, DecisionBuilder* const db2,
2388  DecisionBuilder* const db3);
2389  DecisionBuilder* Try(DecisionBuilder* const db1, DecisionBuilder* const db2,
2390  DecisionBuilder* const db3, DecisionBuilder* const db4);
2391  DecisionBuilder* Try(const std::vector<DecisionBuilder*>& dbs);

2598  // Creates a local search operator that tries to move the assignment of some

2600  // operator generates neighbors in which the only difference compared to the

2605  // Creates a local search operator that tries to move the assignment of some
2606  // variables toward a target. The target is given either as two vectors: a
2607  // vector of variables and a vector of associated target values. The two
2608  // vectors should be of the same length. This operator generates neighbors in
2609  // which the only difference compared to the current state is that one
2610  // variable that belongs to the given vector is set to its target value.

2614 
2615  // Creates a local search operator which concatenates a vector of operators.
2616  // Each operator from the vector is called sequentially. By default, when a
2617  // neighbor is found the neighborhood exploration restarts from the last
2618  // active operator (the one which produced the neighbor).
2619  // This can be overridden by setting restart to true to force the exploration
2620  // to start from the first operator in the vector.
2621  // The default behavior can also be overridden using an evaluation callback to
2622  // set the order in which the operators are explored (the callback is called
2623  // in LocalSearchOperator::Start()). The first argument of the callback is
2624  // the index of the operator which produced the last move, the second
2625  // argument is the index of the operator to be evaluated.
2626  // Ownership of the callback is taken by ConcatenateOperators.
2627  //
2628  // Example:
2629  //
2630  // const int kPriorities = {10, 100, 10, 0};
2631  // int64 Evaluate(int active_operator, int current_operator) {
2632  // return kPriorities[current_operator];
2633  // }
2634  //
2635  // LocalSearchOperator* concat =
2636  // solver.ConcatenateOperators(operators,
2637  // NewPermanentCallback(&Evaluate));
2638  //
2639  // The elements of the vector operators will be sorted by increasing priority
2640  // and explored in that order (tie-breaks are handled by keeping the relative
2641  // operator order in the vector). This would result in the following order:
2642  // operators[3], operators[0], operators[2], operators[1].
2643  //
2644  LocalSearchOperator* ConcatenateOperators(
2645  const std::vector<LocalSearchOperator*>& ops);
2646  LocalSearchOperator* ConcatenateOperators(
2647  const std::vector<LocalSearchOperator*>& ops, bool restart);
2648  LocalSearchOperator* ConcatenateOperators(
2649  const std::vector<LocalSearchOperator*>& ops,
2650  std::function<int64(int, int)> evaluator);
2651  // Randomized version of local search concatenator; calls a random operator
2652  // at each call to MakeNextNeighbor().
2653  LocalSearchOperator* RandomConcatenateOperators(
2654  const std::vector<LocalSearchOperator*>& ops);
2655 
2656  // Randomized version of local search concatenator; calls a random operator
2657  // at each call to MakeNextNeighbor(). The provided seed is used to
2658  // initialize the random number generator.
2659  LocalSearchOperator* RandomConcatenateOperators(
2660  const std::vector<LocalSearchOperator*>& ops, int32 seed);
2661 
2662  // Creates a local search operator that wraps another local search
2663  // operator and limits the number of neighbors explored (i.e., calls
2664  // to MakeNextNeighbor from the current solution (between two calls
2665  // to Start()). When this limit is reached, MakeNextNeighbor()
2666  // returns false. The counter is cleared when Start() is called.
2667  LocalSearchOperator* MakeNeighborhoodLimit(LocalSearchOperator* const op,
2668  int64 limit);
2669 
2670  // Local Search decision builders factories.
2671  // Local search is used to improve a given solution. This initial solution
2672  // can be specified either by an Assignment or by a DecisionBulder, and the
2673  // corresponding variables, the initial solution being the first solution
2674  // found by the DecisionBuilder.
2675  // The LocalSearchPhaseParameters parameter holds the actual definition of
2676  // the local search phase:
2677  // - a local search operator used to explore the neighborhood of the current
2678  // solution,
2679  // - a decision builder to instantiate unbound variables once a neighbor has
2680  // been defined; in the case of LNS-based operators instantiates fragment
2681  // variables; search monitors can be added to this sub-search by wrapping
2682  // the decision builder with MakeSolveOnce.
2683  // - a search limit specifying how long local search looks for neighbors
2684  // before accepting one; the last neighbor is always taken and in the case
2685  // of a greedy search, this corresponds to the best local neighbor;
2686  // first-accept (which is the default behavior) can be modeled using a
2687  // solution found limit of 1,
2688  // - a vector of local search filters used to speed up the search by pruning
2689  // unfeasible neighbors.
2690  // Metaheuristics can be added by defining specialized search monitors;
2691  // currently down/up-hill climbing is available through OptimizeVar, as well
2692  // as Guided Local Search, Tabu Search and Simulated Annealing.
2693  //
2694  // TODO(user): Make a variant which runs a local search after each
2695  // solution found in a DFS.
2696 
2697  DecisionBuilder* MakeLocalSearchPhase(
2698  Assignment* const assignment,
2699  LocalSearchPhaseParameters* const parameters);
2700  DecisionBuilder* MakeLocalSearchPhase(
2701  const std::vector<IntVar*>& vars, DecisionBuilder* const first_solution,
2702  LocalSearchPhaseParameters* const parameters);
2703  // Variant with a sub_decison_builder specific to the first solution.
2704  DecisionBuilder* MakeLocalSearchPhase(
2705  const std::vector<IntVar*>& vars, DecisionBuilder* const first_solution,
2706  DecisionBuilder* const first_solution_sub_decision_builder,
2707  LocalSearchPhaseParameters* const parameters);
2708  DecisionBuilder* MakeLocalSearchPhase(
2709  const std::vector<SequenceVar*>& vars,
2710  DecisionBuilder* const first_solution,
2711  LocalSearchPhaseParameters* const parameters);

3126 // A BaseObject is the root of all reversibly allocated objects.
3127 // A DebugString method and the associated << operator are implemented
3128 // as a convenience.
3129 
3130 class BaseObject {
3131  public:
3132  BaseObject() {}
3133  virtual ~BaseObject() {}
3134  virtual std::string DebugString() const { return "BaseObject"; }
3135 
3136  private:
3137  DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN(BaseObject);
3138 };
3139 
3140 std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream& out, const BaseObject* o); // NOLINT
3141 
3142 // The PropagationBaseObject is a subclass of BaseObject that is also
3143 // friend to the Solver class. It allows accessing methods useful when
3144 // writing new constraints or new expressions.
3145 class PropagationBaseObject : public BaseObject {
3146  public:
3147  explicit PropagationBaseObject(Solver* const s) : solver_(s) {}
3148  ~PropagationBaseObject() override {}
3149 
3150  std::string DebugString() const override {
3151  if (name().empty()) {
3152  return "PropagationBaseObject";
3153  } else {
3154  return absl::StrFormat("PropagationBaseObject: %s", name());
3155  }
3156  }
3157  Solver* solver() const { return solver_; }
3158  // This method freezes the propagation queue. It is useful when you
3159  // need to apply multiple modifications at once.
3160  void FreezeQueue() { solver_->FreezeQueue(); }
3161 
3162  // This method unfreezes the propagation queue. All modifications
3163  // that happened when the queue was frozen will be processed.
3164  void UnfreezeQueue() { solver_->UnfreezeQueue(); }
3165 
3166  // This method pushes the demon onto the propagation queue. It will
3167  // be processed directly if the queue is empty. It will be enqueued
3168  // according to its priority otherwise.
3169  void EnqueueDelayedDemon(Demon* const d) { solver_->EnqueueDelayedDemon(d); }
3170  void EnqueueVar(Demon* const d) { solver_->EnqueueVar(d); }
3171  void ExecuteAll(const SimpleRevFIFO<Demon*>& demons);
3172  void EnqueueAll(const SimpleRevFIFO<Demon*>& demons);
3173 
3174 #if !defined(SWIG)
3175  // This method sets a callback that will be called if a failure
3176  // happens during the propagation of the queue.
3177  void set_action_on_fail(Solver::Action a) {
3178  solver_->set_action_on_fail(std::move(a));
3179  }
3180 #endif // !defined(SWIG)
3181 
3182  // This method clears the failure callback.
3183  void reset_action_on_fail() { solver_->reset_action_on_fail(); }
3184 
3185  // Shortcut for variable cleaner.
3186  void set_variable_to_clean_on_fail(IntVar* v) {
3187  solver_->set_variable_to_clean_on_fail(v);
3188  }
3189 
3190  // Object naming.
3191  virtual std::string name() const;
3192  void set_name(const std::string& name);
3193  // Returns whether the object has been named or not.
3194  bool HasName() const;
3195  // Returns a base name for automatic naming.
3196  virtual std::string BaseName() const;
3197 
3198  private:
3199  Solver* const solver_;
3200  DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN(PropagationBaseObject);
3201 };

3203 // A Decision represents a choice point in the search tree. The two main
3204 // methods are Apply() to go left, or Refute() to go right.
3205 class Decision : public BaseObject {
3206  public:
3207  Decision() {}
3208  ~Decision() override {}
3209 
3210  // Apply will be called first when the decision is executed.
3211  virtual void Apply(Solver* const s) = 0;
3212 
3213  // Refute will be called after a backtrack.
3214  virtual void Refute(Solver* const s) = 0;
3215 
3216  std::string DebugString() const override { return "Decision"; }
3217  // Accepts the given visitor.
3218  virtual void Accept(DecisionVisitor* const visitor) const;
3219 
3220  private:
3221  DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN(Decision);
3222 };

3232  bool start_with_lower_half);

3234  virtual void VisitScheduleOrExpedite(IntervalVar* const var, int64 est);

3236  virtual void VisitRankLastInterval(SequenceVar* const sequence, int index);

3243 // A DecisionBuilder is responsible for creating the search tree. The
3244 // important method is Next(), which returns the next decision to execute.
3245 class DecisionBuilder : public BaseObject {
3246  public:
3247  DecisionBuilder() {}
3248  ~DecisionBuilder() override {}
3249  // This is the main method of the decision builder class. It must
3250  // return a decision (an instance of the class Decision). If it
3251  // returns nullptr, this means that the decision builder has finished
3252  // its work.
3253  virtual Decision* Next(Solver* const s) = 0;
3254  std::string DebugString() const override;
3255 #if !defined(SWIG)
3256  // This method will be called at the start of the search. It asks
3257  // the decision builder if it wants to append search monitors to the
3258  // list of active monitors for this search. Please note there are no
3259  // checks at this point for duplication.
3260  virtual void AppendMonitors(Solver* const solver,
3261  std::vector<SearchMonitor*>* const extras);
3262  virtual void Accept(ModelVisitor* const visitor) const;
3263 #endif
3264 
3265  private:
3266  DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN(DecisionBuilder);
3267 };
3268 
3269 // A Demon is the base element of a propagation queue. It is the main
3270 // object responsible for implementing the actual propagation
3271 // of the constraint and pruning the inconsistent values in the domains
3272 // of the variables. The main concept is that demons are listeners that are
3273 // attached to the variables and listen to their modifications.
3274 // There are two methods:
3275 // - Run() is the actual method called when the demon is processed.
3276 // - priority() returns its priority. Standard priorities are slow, normal
3277 // or fast. "immediate" is reserved for variables and is treated separately.
3278 class Demon : public BaseObject {
3279  public:
3280  // This indicates the priority of a demon. Immediate demons are treated
3281  // separately and corresponds to variables.
3282  Demon() : stamp_(GG_ULONGLONG(0)) {}
3283  ~Demon() override {}
3284 
3285  // This is the main callback of the demon.
3286  virtual void Run(Solver* const s) = 0;
3287 
3288  // This method returns the priority of the demon. Usually a demon is
3289  // fast, slow or normal. Immediate demons are reserved for internal
3290  // use to maintain variables.
3291  virtual Solver::DemonPriority priority() const;
3292 
3293  std::string DebugString() const override;
3294 
3295  // This method inhibits the demon in the search tree below the
3296  // current position.
3297  void inhibit(Solver* const s);
3298 
3299  // This method un-inhibits the demon that was previously inhibited.
3300  void desinhibit(Solver* const s);
3301 
3302  private:
3303  friend class Queue;
3304  void set_stamp(int64 stamp) { stamp_ = stamp; }
3305  uint64 stamp() const { return stamp_; }
3306  uint64 stamp_;
3307  DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN(Demon);
3308 };

3555 // A constraint is the main modeling object. It provides two methods:
3556 // - Post() is responsible for creating the demons and attaching them to
3557 // immediate demons().
3558 // - InitialPropagate() is called once just after Post and performs
3559 // the initial propagation. The subsequent propagations will be performed
3560 // by the demons Posted during the post() method.
3561 class Constraint : public PropagationBaseObject {
3562  public:
3563  explicit Constraint(Solver* const solver) : PropagationBaseObject(solver) {}
3564  ~Constraint() override {}
3565 
3566  // This method is called when the constraint is processed by the
3567  // solver. Its main usage is to attach demons to variables.
3568  virtual void Post() = 0;
3569 
3570  // This method performs the initial propagation of the
3571  // constraint. It is called just after the post.
3572  virtual void InitialPropagate() = 0;
3573  std::string DebugString() const override;
3574 
3575  // Calls Post and then Propagate to initialize the constraints. This
3576  // is usually done in the root node.
3577  void PostAndPropagate();
3578 
3579  // Accepts the given visitor.
3580  virtual void Accept(ModelVisitor* const visitor) const;
3581 
3582  // Is the constraint created by a cast from expression to integer variable?
3583  bool IsCastConstraint() const;
3584 
3585  // Creates a Boolean variable representing the status of the constraint (false
3586  // = constraint is violated, true = constraint is satisfied). It returns
3587  // nullptr if the constraint does not support this API.
3588  virtual IntVar* Var();
3589 
3590  private:
3591  DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN(Constraint);
3592 };
3593 
3594 // Cast constraints are special channeling constraints designed
3595 // to keep a variable in sync with an expression. They are
3596 // created internally when Var() is called on a subclass of IntExpr.
3597 class CastConstraint : public Constraint {
3598  public:
3599  CastConstraint(Solver* const solver, IntVar* const target_var)
3600  : Constraint(solver), target_var_(target_var) {
3601  CHECK(target_var != nullptr);
3602  }
3603  ~CastConstraint() override {}
3604 
3605  IntVar* target_var() const { return target_var_; }
3606 
3607  protected:
3608  IntVar* const target_var_;
3609 };

3611 // A search monitor is a simple set of callbacks to monitor all search events
3612 class SearchMonitor : public BaseObject {
3613  public:
3614  static const int kNoProgress = -1;
3615 
3616  explicit SearchMonitor(Solver* const s) : solver_(s) {}
3617  ~SearchMonitor() override {}
3618  // Beginning of the search.
3619  virtual void EnterSearch();
3620 
3621  // Restart the search.
3622  virtual void RestartSearch();
3623 
3624  // End of the search.
3625  virtual void ExitSearch();
3626 
3627  // Before calling DecisionBuilder::Next.
3628  virtual void BeginNextDecision(DecisionBuilder* const b);
3629 
3630  // After calling DecisionBuilder::Next, along with the returned decision.
3631  virtual void EndNextDecision(DecisionBuilder* const b, Decision* const d);
3632 
3633  // Before applying the decision.
3634  virtual void ApplyDecision(Decision* const d);
3635 
3636  // Before refuting the decision.
3637  virtual void RefuteDecision(Decision* const d);
3638 
3639  // Just after refuting or applying the decision, apply is true after Apply.
3640  // This is called only if the Apply() or Refute() methods have not failed.
3641  virtual void AfterDecision(Decision* const d, bool apply);
3642 
3643  // Just when the failure occurs.
3644  virtual void BeginFail();
3645 
3646  // After completing the backtrack.
3647  virtual void EndFail();
3648 
3649  // Before the initial propagation.
3650  virtual void BeginInitialPropagation();
3651 
3652  // After the initial propagation.
3653  virtual void EndInitialPropagation();
3654 
3655  // This method is called when a solution is found. It asserts whether the
3656  // solution is valid. A value of false indicates that the solution
3657  // should be discarded.
3658  virtual bool AcceptSolution();
3659 
3660  // This method is called when a valid solution is found. If the
3661  // return value is true, then search will resume after. If the result
3662  // is false, then search will stop there.
3663  virtual bool AtSolution();
3664 
3665  // When the search tree is finished.
3666  virtual void NoMoreSolutions();
3667 
3668  // When a local optimum is reached. If 'true' is returned, the last solution
3669  // is discarded and the search proceeds with the next one.
3670  virtual bool LocalOptimum();
3671 
3672  //
3673  virtual bool AcceptDelta(Assignment* delta, Assignment* deltadelta);
3674 
3675  // After accepting a neighbor during local search.
3676  virtual void AcceptNeighbor();
3677 
3678  // After accepting an unchecked neighbor during local search.
3679  virtual void AcceptUncheckedNeighbor();
3680 
3681  // Returns true if the limit of solutions has been reached including
3682  // unchecked solutions.
3683  virtual bool IsUncheckedSolutionLimitReached() { return false; }
3684 
3685  Solver* solver() const { return solver_; }
3686 
3687  // Periodic call to check limits in long running methods.
3688  virtual void PeriodicCheck();
3689 
3690  // Returns a percentage representing the propress of the search before
3691  // reaching limits.
3692  virtual int ProgressPercent() { return kNoProgress; }
3693 
3694  // Accepts the given model visitor.
3695  virtual void Accept(ModelVisitor* const visitor) const;
3696 
3697  // Registers itself on the solver such that it gets notified of the search
3698  // and propagation events.
3699  virtual void Install();
3700 
3701  private:
3702  Solver* const solver_;
3703  DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN(SearchMonitor);
3704 };

3706 // This class adds reversibility to a POD type.
3707 // It contains the stamp optimization. i.e. the SaveValue call is done
3708 // only once per node of the search tree. Please note that actual
3709 // stamps always starts at 1, thus an initial value of 0 will always
3710 // trigger the first SaveValue.
3711 template <class T>
3712 class Rev {
3713  public:
3714  explicit Rev(const T& val) : stamp_(0), value_(val) {}
3715 
3716  const T& Value() const { return value_; }
3717 
3718  void SetValue(Solver* const s, const T& val) {
3719  if (val != value_) {
3720  if (stamp_ < s->stamp()) {
3721  s->SaveValue(&value_);
3722  stamp_ = s->stamp();
3723  }
3724  value_ = val;
3725  }
3726  }
3727 
3728  private:
3729  uint64 stamp_;
3730  T value_;
3731 };
3732 
3733 // Subclass of Rev<T> which adds numerical operations.
3734 template <class T>
3735 class NumericalRev : public Rev<T> {
3736  public:
3737  explicit NumericalRev(const T& val) : Rev<T>(val) {}
3738 
3739  void Add(Solver* const s, const T& to_add) {
3740  this->SetValue(s, this->Value() + to_add);
3741  }
3742 
3743  void Incr(Solver* const s) { Add(s, 1); }
3744 
3745  void Decr(Solver* const s) { Add(s, -1); }
3746 };
3747 
3748 // Reversible array of POD types.
3749 // It contains the stamp optimization. I.e., the SaveValue call is done only
3750 // once per node of the search tree.
3751 // Please note that actual stamp always starts at 1, thus an initial value of
3752 // 0 always triggers the first SaveValue.
3753 template <class T>
3754 class RevArray {
3755  public:
3756  RevArray(int size, const T& val)
3757  : stamps_(new uint64[size]), values_(new T[size]), size_(size) {
3758  for (int i = 0; i < size; ++i) {
3759  stamps_[i] = 0;
3760  values_[i] = val;
3761  }
3762  }
3763 
3764  ~RevArray() {}
3765 
3766  int64 size() const { return size_; }
3767 
3768  const T& Value(int index) const { return values_[index]; }
3769 
3770 #if !defined(SWIG)
3771  const T& operator[](int index) const { return values_[index]; }
3772 #endif
3773 
3774  void SetValue(Solver* const s, int index, const T& val) {
3775  DCHECK_LT(index, size_);
3776  if (val != values_[index]) {
3777  if (stamps_[index] < s->stamp()) {
3778  s->SaveValue(&values_[index]);
3779  stamps_[index] = s->stamp();
3780  }
3781  values_[index] = val;
3782  }
3783  }
3784 
3785  private:
3786  std::unique_ptr<uint64[]> stamps_;
3787  std::unique_ptr<T[]> values_;
3788  const int size_;
3789 };
3790 
3791 // Subclass of RevArray<T> which adds numerical operations.
3792 template <class T>
3793 class NumericalRevArray : public RevArray<T> {
3794  public:
3795  NumericalRevArray(int size, const T& val) : RevArray<T>(size, val) {}
3796 
3797  void Add(Solver* const s, int index, const T& to_add) {
3798  this->SetValue(s, index, this->Value(index) + to_add);
3799  }
3800 
3801  void Incr(Solver* const s, int index) { Add(s, index, 1); }
3802 
3803  void Decr(Solver* const s, int index) { Add(s, index, -1); }
3804 };

3806 // The class IntExpr is the base of all integer expressions in
3807 // constraint programming.
3808 // It contains the basic protocol for an expression:
3809 // - setting and modifying its bound
3810 // - querying if it is bound
3811 // - listening to events modifying its bounds
3812 // - casting it into a variable (instance of IntVar)
3813 class IntExpr : public PropagationBaseObject {
3814  public:
3815  explicit IntExpr(Solver* const s) : PropagationBaseObject(s) {}
3816  ~IntExpr() override {}
3817 
3818  virtual int64 Min() const = 0;
3819  virtual void SetMin(int64 m) = 0;
3820  virtual int64 Max() const = 0;
3821  virtual void SetMax(int64 m) = 0;
3822 
3823  // By default calls Min() and Max(), but can be redefined when Min and Max
3824  // code can be factorized.
3825  virtual void Range(int64* l, int64* u) {
3826  *l = Min();
3827  *u = Max();
3828  }
3829  // This method sets both the min and the max of the expression.
3830  virtual void SetRange(int64 l, int64 u) {
3831  SetMin(l);
3832  SetMax(u);
3833  }
3834 
3835  // This method sets the value of the expression.
3836  virtual void SetValue(int64 v) { SetRange(v, v); }
3837 
3838  // Returns true if the min and the max of the expression are equal.
3839  virtual bool Bound() const { return (Min() == Max()); }
3840 
3841  // Returns true if the expression is indeed a variable.
3842  virtual bool IsVar() const { return false; }
3843 
3844  // Creates a variable from the expression.
3845  virtual IntVar* Var() = 0;
3846 
3847  // Creates a variable from the expression and set the name of the
3848  // resulting var. If the expression is already a variable, then it
3849  // will set the name of the expression, possibly overwriting it.
3850  // This is just a shortcut to Var() followed by set_name().
3851  IntVar* VarWithName(const std::string& name);
3852 
3853  // Attach a demon that will watch the min or the max of the expression.
3854  virtual void WhenRange(Demon* d) = 0;
3855  // Attach a demon that will watch the min or the max of the expression.
3856  void WhenRange(Solver::Closure closure) {
3857  WhenRange(solver()->MakeClosureDemon(std::move(closure)));
3858  }
3859 
3860 #if !defined(SWIG)
3861  // Attach a demon that will watch the min or the max of the expression.
3862  void WhenRange(Solver::Action action) {
3863  WhenRange(solver()->MakeActionDemon(std::move(action)));
3864  }
3865 #endif // SWIG
3866 
3867  // Accepts the given visitor.
3868  virtual void Accept(ModelVisitor* const visitor) const;
3869 
3870  private:
3871  DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN(IntExpr);
3872 };

3874 // The class Iterator has two direct subclasses. HoleIterators
3875 // iterates over all holes, that is value removed between the
3876 // current min and max of the variable since the last time the
3877 // variable was processed in the queue. DomainIterators iterates
3878 // over all elements of the variable domain. Both iterators are not
3879 // robust to domain changes. Hole iterators can also report values outside
3880 // the current min and max of the variable.
3881 
3882 // HoleIterators should only be called from a demon attached to the
3883 // variable that has created this iterator.
3884 
3885 // IntVar* current_var;
3886 // std::unique_ptr<IntVarIterator> it(current_var->MakeHoleIterator(false));
3887 // for (const int64 hole : InitAndGetValues(it)) {
3888 // // use the hole
3889 // }
3890 
3891 class IntVarIterator : public BaseObject {
3892  public:
3893  ~IntVarIterator() override {}
3894 
3895  // This method must be called before each loop.
3896  virtual void Init() = 0;
3897 
3898  // This method indicates if we can call Value() or not.
3899  virtual bool Ok() const = 0;
3900 
3901  // This method returns the current value of the iterator.
3902  virtual int64 Value() const = 0;
3903 
3904  // This method moves the iterator to the next value.
3905  virtual void Next() = 0;
3906 
3907  // Pretty Print.
3908  std::string DebugString() const override { return "IntVar::Iterator"; }
3909 };

3911 #ifndef SWIG
3912 // Utility class to encapsulate an IntVarIterator and use it in a range-based
3913 // loop. See the code snippet above IntVarIterator.
3914 //
3915 // It contains DEBUG_MODE-enabled code that DCHECKs that the
3916 // same iterator instance isn't being iterated on in multiple places
3917 // simultaneously.
3918 class InitAndGetValues {
3919  public:
3920  explicit InitAndGetValues(IntVarIterator* it)
3921  : it_(it), begin_was_called_(false) {
3922  it_->Init();
3923  }
3924  struct Iterator;
3925  Iterator begin() {
3926  if (DEBUG_MODE) {
3927  DCHECK(!begin_was_called_);
3928  begin_was_called_ = true;
3929  }
3930  return Iterator::Begin(it_);
3931  }
3932  Iterator end() { return Iterator::End(it_); }
3933 
3934  struct Iterator {
3935  // These are the only way to construct an Iterator.
3936  static Iterator Begin(IntVarIterator* it) {
3937  return Iterator(it, /*is_end=*/false);
3938  }
3939  static Iterator End(IntVarIterator* it) {
3940  return Iterator(it, /*is_end=*/true);
3941  }
3942 
3943  int64 operator*() const {
3944  DCHECK(it_->Ok());
3945  return it_->Value();
3946  }
3947  Iterator& operator++() {
3948  DCHECK(it_->Ok());
3949  it_->Next();
3950  return *this;
3951  }
3952  bool operator!=(const Iterator& other) const {
3953  DCHECK(other.it_ == it_);
3954  DCHECK(other.is_end_);
3955  return it_->Ok();
3956  }
3957 
3958  private:
3959  Iterator(IntVarIterator* it, bool is_end) : it_(it), is_end_(is_end) {}
3960 
3961  IntVarIterator* const it_;
3962  const bool is_end_;
3963  };
3964 
3965  private:
3966  IntVarIterator* const it_;
3967  bool begin_was_called_;
3968 };
3969 #endif // SWIG
